76.jpg?ssl=1"  data-amp-layout="responsive"/></a></figure></div><div class="tiled-gallery__col" style="flex-basis:50.00000%"><figure class="tiled-gallery__item"><a href="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/img_7377-2/"><img  decoding="async" data-srcset="https://i0.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7377.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=600&#038;ssl=1 600w,https://i0.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7377.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=900&#038;ssl=1 900w,https://i0.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7377.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=1024&#038;ssl=1 1024w" alt="" data-height="683" data-id="28026" data-link="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/img_7377-2/" data-url="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7377.jpg" data-width="1024"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://i0.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7377.jpg?ssl=1"  data-amp-layout="responsive"/></a></figure></div></div></div></div>



<p>It&#8217;s not much to look at. That&#8217;s a good sandwich though. My dry-brine and spatchcock method results in chicken that&#8217;s plenty juicy both in the white and dark meat, with a mild smoke flavor that is punctuated by the sauce&#8217;s acidity and heat. The pickles provide a bit of briny crunch to change things up a bit and the squishy hamburger buns are only there to provide a handy, edible carrying case for the other ingredients.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img  loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="683"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7378.jpg"  alt="" class="wp-image-28027" data-srcset="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7378.jpg 1024w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7378-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7378-150x100.jpg 150w" data-sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Smoked chicken with Alabama white sauce on bun with pickle</figcaption></figure>



<p>But today, I also chose to make a sandwich closer to what they serve at Big Bob Gibson&#8217;s, with a whole piece of chicken glazed in white sauce. Only I didn&#8217;t want to use a boring piece of breast meat. So I seasoned some boneless, skinless chicken thighs with the same rub I used for the whole chicken and smoked them, then finished them under the broiler, brushing each side with white sauce 3 times until the water in the sauce boiled away, the remaining fats and sugars caramelizing into thin, crisp shell. Then I served it in a hamburger bun with pickles and a little extra sauce, same as before. </p>



