gure class="tiled-gallery__item"><img  decoding="async" data-srcset="https://i1.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7386.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=600&#038;ssl=1 600w,https://i1.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7386.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=900&#038;ssl=1 900w,https://i1.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7386.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=1024&#038;ssl=1 1024w" alt="" data-height="683" data-id="28031" data-link="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/img_7386/" data-url="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7386.jpg" data-width="1024"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://i1.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7386.jpg?ssl=1"  data-amp-layout="responsive"/></figure></div></div><div class="tiled-gallery__row"><div class="tiled-gallery__col" style="flex-basis:100.00000%"><figure class="tiled-gallery__item"><img  decoding="async" data-srcset="https://i2.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7387.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=600&#038;ssl=1 600w,https://i2.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7387.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=900&#038;ssl=1 900w,https://i2.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7387.jpg?strip=info&#038;w=1024&#038;ssl=1 1024w" alt="" data-height="683" data-id="28032" data-link="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/img_7387/" data-url="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7387.jpg" data-width="1024"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://i2.wp.com/www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7387.jpg?ssl=1"  data-amp-layout="responsive"/></figure></div></div></div></div>



<p>OK. Forget what I said about serving chicken with Alabama white sauce shredded before. <em>This</em> is the way I should be making it from now on. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img  loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="683"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7391.jpg"  alt="" class="wp-image-28033" data-srcset="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7391.jpg 1024w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7391-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7391-150x100.jpg 150w" data-sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Chicken thigh glazed with white sauce on bun with pickle</figcaption></figure>



<p>Chicken thigh is a fatty and forgiving meat that can be cooked and cooked again without drying out and becoming unpleasant, allowing it to remain relatively moist while caramelizing multiple layers of Alabama white sauce on its surface. In fact, I had left these thighs in the smoker too long and was afraid they were overdone, but reheated under the broiler, bathed multiple times in my white sauce, they made the best Alabama white sauce chicken sandwich I&#8217;d had yet. The caramelization brings out the sweetness of the sauce, while taming some of its acidity and heat, but a little extra sauce helps bring some of that back, and of course the pickles are key. </p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="alignright size-full is-resized"><img  loading="lazy" decoding="async"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7428.jpg"  alt="" class="wp-image-28142" width="157" height="235" data-srcset="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7428.jpg 683w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7428-200x300.jpg 200w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7428-100x150.jpg 100w" data-sizes="(max-width: 157px) 100vw, 157px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Big Bob Gibson Bar-B-Q white sauce</figcaption></figure></div>


<p>But &#8220;real&#8221; chicken with white sauce the way they make it at Big Bob Gibson&#8217;s isn&#8217;t done any of the ways I&#8217;ve made it so far. The hickory-smoked chickens are dipped entirely in the white sauce after smoking, then presumably held until they are served. </p>



<p>I am not making and/or buying enough of this white sauce to fill a vat that I can dip a whole chicken into. But I will buy a bottle of the commercially-available version of Big Bob Gibson&#8217;s sauce to try and make this version as close as possible to the real thing. </p>



<p>A long-overdue trip to North Carolina to visit my brother interrupted this sandwich investigation, and when I got back I was not feeling motivated enough to go through my entire laborious process of dry-brining then smoking a chicken. I am lucky enough though to have a good local barbecue joint a couple miles from my house called Exsenators. My usual order from Exsenators is a classic Chicago-style tip-link combo but their smoked chicken&#8211;which comes as a half or &#8220;whole&#8221; chicken with bread and fries usually&#8211;is very well done.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img  loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="683"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7430.jpg"  alt="" class="wp-image-28143" data-srcset="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7430.jpg 1024w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7430-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7430-150x100.jpg 150w" data-sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Smoked chicken from my local, Exsenators in Markham</figcaption></figure>



<p>I picked up the chicken in the late afternoon and brushed it thoroughly with Big Bob&#8217;s white sauce, top and bottom, holding it on a rack over a baking pan until I was ready to serve.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img  loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="1024" height="683"  src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-src="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7437.jpg"  alt="" class="wp-image-28144" data-srcset="https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7437.jpg 1024w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7437-300x200.jpg 300w, https://www.sandwichtribunal.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/IMG_7437-150x100.jpg 150w" data-sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Exsenators chicken coated in white sauce</figcaption></figure>



<p>After an hour or two, much of the sauce had either settled into the little valleys on the surface of the chicken, or dripped off the sides onto the pan, leaving the skin glistening but without much visible sauce. I brushed a little more on, tented some foil over the pan, and heated the chicken at 350° for 15 minutes </p>



